atches all presumed valid inputs, it is declared to be production-ready and can be included in a released application.","pos":[2255,2391]},{"content":"This makes a regular expression pattern suitable for matching constrained input.","pos":[2392,2472]},{"content":"However, it does not make it suitable for matching unconstrained input.","pos":[2473,2544]},{"content":"To match unconstrained input, a regular expression must be able to efficiently handle three kinds of text:","pos":[2551,2657]},{"content":"Text that matches the regular expression pattern.","pos":[2667,2716]},{"content":"Text that does not match the regular expression pattern.","pos":[2726,2782]},{"content":"Text that nearly matches the regular expression pattern.","pos":[2792,2848]},{"content":"The last text type is especially problematic for a regular expression that has been written to handle constrained input.","pos":[2855,2975]},{"content":"If that regular expression also relies on extensive <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>backtracking<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../docs/standard/base-types/backtracking-in-regular-expressions.md)</ept>, the regular expression engine can spend an inordinate amount of time (in some cases, many hours or days) processing seemingly innocuous text.","pos":[2976,3259],"source":" If that regular expression also relies on extensive [backtracking](../../../docs/standard/base-types/backtracking-in-regular-expressions.md), the regular expression engine can spend an inordinate amount of time (in some cases, many hours or days) processing seemingly innocuous text."},{"pos":[3267,3697],"content":"[!WARNING]\n The following example uses a regular expression that is prone to excessive backtracking and that is likely to reject valid email addresses. You should not use it in an email validation routine. If you would like a regular expression that validates email addresses, see [How to: Verify that Strings Are in Valid Email Format](../../../docs/standard/base-types/how-to-verify-that-strings-are-in-va