eric, periods, or hyphens."},{"content":"The regular expression must end with an alphanumeric character.","pos":[4090,4153]},{"content":"However, as the following example shows, although this regular expression handles valid input easily, its performance is very inefficient when it is processing nearly valid input.","pos":[4154,4333]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[!code-csharp</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#1<ept id=\"p2\">](../../../samples/snippets/csharp/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/cs/design2.cs#1)</ept><ept id=\"p1\">]</ept>","pos":[4340,4511],"source":"[!code-csharp[Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#1](../../../samples/snippets/csharp/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/cs/design2.cs#1)]"},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[!code-vb</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#1<ept id=\"p2\">](../../../samples/snippets/visualbasic/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/vb/design2.vb#1)</ept><ept id=\"p1\">]</ept>","pos":[4513,4685],"source":"[!code-vb[Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#1](../../../samples/snippets/visualbasic/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/vb/design2.vb#1)]"},{"content":"As the output from the example shows, the regular expression engine processes the valid email alias in about the same time interval regardless of its length.","pos":[4692,4849]},{"content":"On the other hand, when the nearly valid email address has more than five characters, processing time approximately doubles for each additional character in the string.","pos":[4850,5018]},{"content":"This means that a nearly valid 28-character string would take over an hour to process, and a nearly valid 33-character string would take nearly a day to process.","pos":[5019,5180]},{"content":"Because this regular expression was developed solely by considering the format of input to be matched, it fails to take account of input that does not match the pattern.","pos":[5187,5356]},{"content":"This, in turn, can allow unconstrained input that nearly matches the regular expression pattern to significantly degrade performance.","pos":[5357,5490]},{"content":"To solve this problem, you can do the following:","pos":[5497,5545]},{"content":"When developing a pattern, you should consider how backtracking might affect the performance of the regular expression engine, particularly if your regular expression is designed to process unconstrained input.","pos":[5555,5765]},{"content":"For more information, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Take Charge of Backtracking<ept id=\"p1\">](#Backtracking)</ept> section.","pos":[5766,5849],"source":" For more information, see the [Take Charge of Backtracking](#Backtracking) section."},{"content":"Thoroughly test your regular expression using invalid and near-valid input as well as valid input.","pos":[5859,5957]},{"content":"To generate input for a particular regular expression randomly, you can use <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Rex<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=210756)</ept>, which is a regular expression exploration tool from Microsoft Research.","pos":[5958,6159],"source":" To generate input for a particular regular expression randomly, you can use [Rex](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=210756), which is a regular expression exploration tool from Microsoft Research."},{"pos":[6166,6185],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Back to top<ept id=\"p1\">](#top)</ept>","source":"[Back to top](#top)"},{"pos":[6232,6273],"content":"Handle Object Instantiation Appropriately","linkify":"Handle Object Instantiation Appropriately","nodes":[{"content":"Handle Object Instantiation Appropriately","pos":[0,41]}]},{"content":"At the heart of .NETâ€™s regular expression object model is the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.RegularExpressions.Regex?displayProperty=fullName&gt;</ph> class, which represents the regular expression engine.","pos":[6