ractices#3<ept id=\"p2\">](../../../samples/snippets/csharp/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/cs/static1.cs#3)</ept><ept id=\"p1\">]</ept>","pos":[11002,11173],"source":"[!code-csharp[Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#3](../../../samples/snippets/csharp/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/cs/static1.cs#3)]"},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[!code-vb</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#3<ept id=\"p2\">](../../../samples/snippets/visualbasic/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/vb/static1.vb#3)</ept><ept id=\"p1\">]</ept>","pos":[11175,11347],"source":"[!code-vb[Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#3](../../../samples/snippets/visualbasic/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/vb/static1.vb#3)]"},{"content":"You should replace this inefficient code with a call to the static <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.RegularExpressions.Regex.IsMatch%28System.String%2CSystem.String%29?displayProperty=fullName&gt;</ph> method.","pos":[11354,11540],"source":"You should replace this inefficient code with a call to the static <xref:System.Text.RegularExpressions.Regex.IsMatch%28System.String%2CSystem.String%29?displayProperty=fullName> method."},{"content":"This eliminates the need to instantiate a <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.RegularExpressions.Regex&gt;</ph> object each time you want to call a pattern-matching method, and enables the regular expression engine to retrieve a compiled version of the regular expression from its cache.","pos":[11541,11802],"source":" This eliminates the need to instantiate a <xref:System.Text.RegularExpressions.Regex> object each time you want to call a pattern-matching method, and enables the regular expression engine to retrieve a compiled version of the regular expression from its cache."},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[!code-csharp</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#4<ept id=\"p2\">](../../../samples/snippets/csharp/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/cs/static2.cs#4)</ept><ept id=\"p1\">]</ept>","pos":[11809,11980],"source":"[!code-csharp[Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#4](../../../samples/snippets/csharp/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/cs/static2.cs#4)]"},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[!code-vb</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#4<ept id=\"p2\">](../../../samples/snippets/visualbasic/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/vb/static2.vb#4)</ept><ept id=\"p1\">]</ept>","pos":[11982,12154],"source":"[!code-vb[Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#4](../../../samples/snippets/visualbasic/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/vb/static2.vb#4)]"},{"content":"By default, the last 15 most recently used static regular expression patterns are cached.","pos":[12161,12250]},{"content":"For applications that require a larger number of cached static regular expressions, the size of the cache can be adjusted by setting the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.RegularExpressions.Regex.CacheSize%2A?displayProperty=fullName&gt;</ph> property.","pos":[12251,12479],"source":" For applications that require a larger number of cached static regular expressions, the size of the cache can be adjusted by setting the <xref:System.Text.RegularExpressions.Regex.CacheSize%2A?displayProperty=fullName> property."},{"content":"The regular expression <ph id=\"ph1\">`\\p{Sc}+\\s*\\d+`</ph> that is used in this example verifies that the input string consists of a currency symbol and at least one decimal digit.","pos":[12486,12646],"source":"The regular expression `\\p{Sc}+\\s*\\d+` that is used in this example verifies that the input string consists of a currency symbol and at least one decimal digit."},{"content":"The pattern is defined as shown in the following table.","pos":[12647,12702]},{"content":"Pattern","pos":[12709,12716]},{"content":"Description","pos":[12717,12728]},{"content":"Match one or more characters in the Unicode Symbol, Currency category.","pos":[12779,12849]},{"content":"Match zero or more white-space characters.","pos":[12860,12902]},{"content":"Match one or more decimal digits.","pos":[12913,12946]},{"pos":[12987,13031],"content":"Interpreted vs. Compiled Regular Expressions","linkify":"Interpreted vs. Compiled Regular Expressions","nodes":[{"content":"Interpreted vs. Compiled Regular Expressions","pos":[0,44]}]},{"content":"Regular expression patterns that are not bound to the regular expression engine through the specification of the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.RegularExpressions.RegexOptions&gt;</ph> option are interpreted.","pos":[13035,13222],"source":"Regular expression patterns that are not bound to the regular expression engine through the specification of the <xref:System.Text.RegularExpressions.RegexOptions> option are interpreted."},{"content":"When a regular expression object is instantiated, the regular expression engine converts the regular expression to a set of operation codes.","pos":[13223,13363]},{"content":"When an instance method is called, the operation codes are converted to MSIL and executed by the JIT compiler.","pos":[13364,13474]},{"content":"Similarly, when a static regular expression method is called and the regular expression cannot be found in the cache, the regular expression engine converts the regular expression to a set of operation codes and stores them in the cache.","pos":[13475,13712]},{"content":"It then converts these operation codes to MSIL so that the JIT compiler can execute them.","pos":[13713,13802]},{"content":"Interpreted regular expressions reduce startup time at the cost of slower execution time.","pos":[13803,13892]},{"content":"Because of this, they are best used when the regular expression is used in a small number of method calls, or if the exact number of calls to regular expression methods is unknown but is expected to be small.","pos":[13893,14101]},{"content":"As the number of method calls increases, the performance gain from reduced startup time is outstripped by the slower execution speed.","pos":[14102,14235]},{"content":"Regular expression patterns that are bound to the regular expression engine through the specification of the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.RegularExpressions.RegexOptions&gt;</ph> option are compiled.","pos":[14242,14422],"source":"Regular expression patterns that are bound to the regular expression engine through the specification of the <xref:System.Text.RegularExpressions.RegexOptions> option are compiled."},{"content":"This means that, when a regular expression object is instantiated, or when a static regular expression method is called and the regular expression cannot be found in the cache, the regular expression engine converts the regular expression to an intermediary set of operation codes, which it then converts to MSIL.","pos":[14423,14736]},{"content":"When a method is called, the JIT compiler executes the MSIL.","pos":[14737,14797]},{"content":"In contrast to interpreted regular expressions, compiled regular expressions increase startup time but execute individual pattern-matching methods faster.","pos":[14798,14952]},{"content":"As a result, the performance benefit that results from compiling the regular expression increases in proportion to the number of regular expression methods called.","pos":[14953,15116]},{"content":"To summarize, we recommend that you use interpreted regular expressions when you call regular expression methods with a specific regular expression relatively infrequently.","pos":[15123,15295]},{"content":"You should use compiled regular expressions when you call regular expression methods with a specific regular expression relatively frequently.","pos":[15296,15438]},{"content":"The exact threshold at which the slower execution speeds of interpreted regular expressions outweigh gains from their reduced startup time, or the threshold at which the slower startup times of compiled regular expressions outweigh gains from their faster execution speeds, is difficult to determine.","pos":[15439,15739]},{"content":"It depends on a variety of factors, including the complexity of the regular expression and the specific data that it processes.","pos":[15740,15867]},{"content":"To determine whether interpreted or compiled regular expressions offer the best performance for your particular application scenario, you can use the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Diagnostics.Stopwatch&gt;</ph> class to compare their execution times.","pos":[15868,16093],"source":" To determine whether interpreted or compiled regular expressions offer the best performance for your particular application scenario, you can use the <xref:System.Diagnostics.Stopwatch> class to compare their execution times."},{"content":"The following example compares the performance of compiled and interpreted regular expressions when reading the first ten sentences and when reading all the sentences in the text of Theodore Dreiser's <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>The Financier<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>.","pos":[16100,16317],"source":"The following example compares the performance of compiled and interpreted regular expressions when reading the first ten sentences and when reading all the sentences in the text of Theodore Dreiser's *The Financier*."},{"content":"As the output from the example shows, when only ten calls are made to regular expression matching methods, an interpreted regular expression offers better performance than a compiled regular expression.","pos":[16318,16520]},{"content":"However, a compiled regular expression offers better performance when a large number of calls (in this case, over 13,000) are made.","pos":[16521,16652]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[!code-csharp</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#5<ept id=\"p2\">](../../../samples/snippets/csharp/VS_Snippets_CLR/co