ify":"Regular Expressions: Compiled to an Assembly","nodes":[{"content":"Regular Expressions: Compiled to an Assembly","pos":[0,44]}]},{"content":".NET also enables you to create an assembly that contains compiled regular expressions.","pos":[17878,17965]},{"content":"This moves the performance hit of regular expression compilation from run time to design time.","pos":[17966,18060]},{"content":"However, it also involves some additional work: You must define the regular expressions in advance and compile them to an assembly.","pos":[18061,18192]},{"content":"The compiler can then reference this assembly when compiling source code that uses the assemblyâ€™s regular expressions.","pos":[18193,18311]},{"content":"Each compiled regular expression in the assembly is represented by a class that derives from <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.RegularExpressions.Regex&gt;</ph>.","pos":[18312,18449],"source":" Each compiled regular expression in the assembly is represented by a class that derives from <xref:System.Text.RegularExpressions.Regex>."},{"content":"To compile regular expressions to an assembly, you call the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.RegularExpressions.Regex.CompileToAssembly%28System.Text.RegularExpressions.RegexCompilationInfo%5B%5D%2CSystem.Reflection.AssemblyName%29?displayProperty=fullName&gt;</ph> method and pass it an array of <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Text.RegularExpressions.RegexCompilationInfo&gt;</ph> objects that represent the regular expressions to be compiled, and an <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.Reflection.AssemblyName&gt;</ph> object that contains information about the assembly to be created.","pos":[18456,18963],"source":"To compile regular expressions to an assembly, you call the <xref:System.Text.RegularExpressions.Regex.CompileToAssembly%28System.Text.RegularExpressions.RegexCompilationInfo%5B%5D%2CSystem.Reflection.AssemblyName%29?displayProperty=fullName> method and pass it an array of <xref:System.Text.RegularExpressions.RegexCompilationInfo> objects that represent the regular expressions to be compiled, and an <xref:System.Reflection.AssemblyName> object that contains information about the assembly to be created."},{"content":"We recommend that you compile regular expressions to an assembly in the following situations:","pos":[18970,19063]},{"content":"If you are a component developer who wants to create a library of reusable regular expressions.","pos":[19073,19168]},{"content":"If you expect your regular expression's pattern-matching methods to be called an indeterminate number of times -- anywhere from once or twice to thousands or tens of thousands of times.","pos":[19178,19363]},{"content":"Unlike compiled or interpreted regular expressions, regular expressions that are compiled to separate assemblies offer performance that is consistent regardless of the number of method calls.","pos":[19364,19555]},{"content":"If you are using compiled regular expressions to optimize performance, you should not use reflection to create the assembly, load the regular expression engine, and execute its pattern-matching methods.","pos":[19562,19764]},{"content":"This requires that you avoid building regular expression patterns dynamically, and that you specify any pattern-matching options (such as case-insensitive pattern matching) at the time the assembly is created.","pos":[19765,19974]},{"content":"It also requires that you separate the code that creates the assembly from the code that uses the regular expression.","pos":[19975,20092]},{"content":"The following example shows how to create an assembly that contains a compiled regular expression.","pos":[20099,20197]},{"content":"It creates an assembly named <ph id=\"ph1\">`RegexLib.dll`</ph> with a single regular expression class, <ph id=\"ph2\">`SentencePattern`</ph>, that contains the sentence-matching regular expression pattern used in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Interpreted vs. Compiled Regular Expressions<ept id=\"p1\">](#Interpreted)</ept> section.","pos":[20198,20445],"source":" It creates an assembly named `RegexLib.dll` with a single regular expression class, `SentencePattern`, that contains the sentence-matching regular expression pattern used in the [Interpreted vs. Compiled Regular Expressions](#Interpreted) section."},{"pos":[20452,20799],"content":"[!code-csharp[Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#6](../../../samples/snippets/csharp/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/cs/compile1.cs#6)]\n[!code-vb[Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#6](../../../samples/snippets/visualbasic/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/vb/compile1.vb#6)]","leadings":[""," "],"nodes":[{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[!code-csharp</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#6<ept id=\"p2\">](../../../samples/snippets/csharp/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/cs/compile1.cs#6)</ept><ept id=\"p1\">]</ept>","pos":[0,172],"source":"[!code-csharp[Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#6](../../../samples/snippets/csharp/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/cs/compile1.cs#6)]"},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[!code-vb</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#6<ept id=\"p2\">](../../../samples/snippets/visualbasic/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/vb/compile1.vb#6)</ept><ept id=\"p1\">]</ept>","pos":[173,346],"source":"[!code-vb[Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#6](../../../samples/snippets/visualbasic/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/vb/compile1.vb#6)]"}]},{"content":"When the example is compiled to an executable and run, it creates an assembly named <ph id=\"ph1\">`RegexLib.dll`</ph>.","pos":[20806,20905],"source":"When the example is compiled to an executable and run, it creates an assembly named `RegexLib.dll`."},{"content":"The regular expression is represented by a class named <ph id=\"ph1\">`Utilities.