tual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/vb/compile2.vb#7)]"}]},{"pos":[21576,21595],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Back to top<ept id=\"p1\">](#top)</ept>","source":"[Back to top](#top)"},{"pos":[21635,21662],"content":"Take Charge of Backtracking","linkify":"Take Charge of Backtracking","nodes":[{"content":"Take Charge of Backtracking","pos":[0,27]}]},{"content":"Ordinarily, the regular expression engine uses linear progression to move through an input string and compare it to a regular expression pattern.","pos":[21666,21811]},{"content":"However, when indeterminate quantifiers such as <ph id=\"ph1\">`*`</ph>, <ph id=\"ph2\">`+`</ph>, and <ph id=\"ph3\">`?`</ph> are used in a regular expression pattern, the regular expression engine may give up a portion of successful partial matches and return to a previously saved state in order to search for a successful match for the entire pattern.","pos":[21812,22106],"source":" However, when indeterminate quantifiers such as `*`, `+`, and `?` are used in a regular expression pattern, the regular expression engine may give up a portion of successful partial matches and return to a previously saved state in order to search for a successful match for the entire pattern."},{"content":"This process is known as backtracking.","pos":[22107,22145]},{"pos":[22153,22617],"content":"[!NOTE]\n For more information on backtracking, see [Details of Regular Expression Behavior](../../../docs/standard/base-types/details-of-regular-expression-behavior.md) and [Backtracking](../../../docs/standard/base-types/backtracking-in-regular-expressions.md). For a detailed discussion of backtracking, see [Optimizing Regular Expression Performance, Part II: Taking Charge of Backtracking](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=211567) in the BCL Team blog.","leadings":["","> "],"nodes":[{"content":"For more information on backtracking, see [Details of Regular Expression Behavior](../../../docs/standard/base-types/details-of-regular-expression-behavior.md) and [Backtracking](../../../docs/standard/base-types/backtracking-in-regular-expressions.md). For a detailed discussion of backtracking, see [Optimizing Regular Expression Performance, Part II: Taking Charge of Backtracking](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=211567) in the BCL Team blog.","pos":[9,462],"nodes":[{"content":"For more information on backtracking, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Details of Regular Expression Behavior<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../docs/standard/base-types/details-of-regular-expression-behavior.md)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Backtracking<ept id=\"p2\">](../../../docs/standard/base-types/backtracking-in-regular-expressions.md)</ept>.","pos":[0,253],"source":"For more information on backtracking, see [Details of Regular Expression Behavior](../../../docs/standard/base-types/details-of-regular-expression-behavior.md) and [Backtracking](../../../docs/standard/base-types/backtracking-in-regular-expressions.md)."},{"content":"For a detailed discussion of backtracking, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Optimizing Regular Expression Performance, Part II: Taking Charge of Backtracking<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=211567)</ept> in the BCL Team blog.","pos":[254,453],"source":" For a detailed discussion of backtracking, see [Optimizing Regular Expression Performance, Part II: Taking Charge of Backtracking](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=211567) in the BCL Team blog."}]}]},{"content":"Support for backtracking gives regular expressions power and flexibility.","pos":[22624,22697]},{"content":"It also places the responsibility for controlling the operation of the regular expression engine in the hands of regular expression developers.","pos":[22698,22841]},{"content":"Because developers are often not aware of this responsibility, their misuse of backtracking or reliance on excessive backtracking often plays the most significant role in degrading regular expression performance.","pos":[22842,23054]},{"content":"In a worst-case scenario, execution time can double for each additional character in the input string.","pos":[23055,23157]},{"content":"In fact, by using backtracking excessively, it is easy to create the programmatic equivalent of an endless loop if input nearly matches the regular expression pattern; the regular expression engine may take hours or even days to process a relatively short input string.","pos":[23158,23427]},{"content":"Often, applications pay a performance penalty for using backtracking despite the fact that backtracking is not essential for a match.","pos":[23434,23567]},{"content":"For example, the regular expression <ph id=\"ph1\">`\\b\\p{Lu}\\w*\\b`</ph> matches all words that begin with an uppercase character, as the following table shows.","pos":[23568,23707],"source":" For example, the regular expression `\\b\\p{Lu}\\w*\\b` matches all words that begin with an uppercase character, as the following table shows."},{"content":"Pattern","pos":[23714,23721]},{"content":"Description","pos":[23722,23733]},{"content":"Begin the match at a word boundary.","pos":[23751,23786]},{"content":"Match an uppercase character.","pos":[23800,23829]},{"content":"Match zero or more word characters.","pos":[23840,23875]},{"content":"End the match at a word boundary.","pos":[23885,23918]},{"content":"Because a word boundary is not the same as, or a subset of, a word character, there is no possibility that the regular expression engine will cross a word boundary when matching word characters.","pos":[23926,24120]},{"content":"This means that for this regular expression, backtracking can never contribute to the overall success of any match -- it can only degrade performance, because the regular expression engine is forced to save its state for each successful preliminary match of a word character.","pos":[24121,24396]},{"content":"If you determine that backtracking is not necessary, you can disable it by using the <ph id=\"ph1\">`(?&gt;``subexpression``)`</ph> language element.","pos":[24403,24529],"source":"If you determine that backtracking is not necessary, you can disable it by using the `(?>``subexpression``)` language element."},{"content":"The following example parses an input string by using two regular expressions.","pos":[24530,24608]},{"content":"The first, <ph id=\"ph1\">`\\b\\p{Lu}\\w*\\b`</ph>, relies on backtracking.","pos":[24609,24660],"source":" The first, `\\b\\p{Lu}\\w*\\b`, relies on backtracking."},{"content":"The second, <ph id=\"ph1\">`\\b\\p{Lu}(?&gt;\\w*)\\b`</ph>, disables backtracking.","pos":[24661,24716],"source":" The second, `\\b\\p{Lu}(?>\\w*)\\b`, disables backtracking."},{"content":"As the output from the example shows, they both produce the same result.","pos":[24717,24789]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[!code-csharp</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#10<ept id=\"p2\">](../../../samples/snippets/csharp/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/cs/backtrack2.cs#10)</ept><ept id=\"p1\">]</ept>","pos":[24796,24972],"source":"[!code-csharp[Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#10](../../../samples/snippets/csharp/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/cs/backtrack2.cs#10)]"},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[!code-vb</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#10<ept id=\"p2\">](../../../samples/snippets/visualbasic/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/vb/backtrack2.vb#10)</ept><ept id=\"p1\">]</ept>","pos":[24974,25151],"source":"[!code-vb[Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#10](../../../samples/snippets/visualbasic/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/vb/backtrack2.vb#10)]"},{"content":"In many cases, backtracking is essential for matching a regular expression pattern to input text.","pos":[25158,25255]},{"content":"However, excessive backtracking can severely degrade performance and create the impression that an application has stopped responding.","pos":[25256,25390]},{"content":"In particular, this happens when quantifiers are nested and the text that matches the outer subexpression is a subset of the text that matches the inner subexpression.","pos":[25391,25558]},{"pos":[25566,25829],"content":"[!WARNING]\n In addition to avoiding excessive backtracking, you should use the timeout feature to ensure that excessive backtracking does not severely degrade regular expression performance. For more information, see the [Use Timeout Values](#Timeouts) section.","leadings":["","> "],"nodes":[{"content":"In addition to avoiding excessive backtracking, you should use the timeout feature to ensure that excessive backtracking does not severely degrade regular expression performance. For more information, see the [Use Timeout Values](#Timeouts) section.","pos":[12,261],"nodes":[{"content":"In addition to avoiding excessive backtracking, you should use the timeout feature to ensure that excessive backtracking does not severely degrade regular expression performance.","pos":[0,178]},{"content":"For more information, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Use Timeout Values<ept id=\"p1\">](#Timeouts)</ept> section.","pos":[179,249],"source":" For more information, see the [Use Timeout Values](#Timeouts) section."}]}]},{"content":"For example, the regular expression pattern <ph id=\"ph1\">`^[0-9A-Z]([-.\\w]*[0-9A-Z])*\\$$`</ph> is intended to match a part number that consists of at least one alphanumeric character.","pos":[25836,26001],"source":"For example, the regular expression pattern `^[0-9A-Z]([-.\\w]*[0-9A-Z])*\\$$` is intended to match a part number that consists of at least one alphanumeric character."},{"content":"Any additional characters can consist of an alphanumeric character, a hyphen, an underscore, or a period, though the last character must be alphanumeric.","pos":[26002,26155]},{"content":"A dollar sign terminates the part number.","pos":[26156,26197]},{"content":"In some cases, this regular expression pattern can exhibit extremely poor performance because quantifiers are nested, and because the subexpression <ph id=\"ph1\">`[0-9A-Z]`</ph> is a subset of the subexpression <ph id=\"ph2\">`[-.\\w]*`</ph>.","pos":[26198,26400],"source":" In some cases, this regular expression pattern can exhibit extremely poor performance because quantifiers are nested, and because the subexpression `[0-9A-Z]` is a subset of the subexpression `[-.\\w]*`."},{"content":"In these cases, you can optimize regular expression performance by removing the nested quantifiers and replacing the outer subexpression with a zero-width lookahead or lookbehind assertion.","pos":[26407,26596]},{"content":"Lookahead and lookbehind assertions are anchors; they do not move the pointer in the input string, but instead look ahead or behind to check whether a specified condition is met.","pos":[26597,26775]},{"content":"For example, the part number regular expression can be rewritten as <ph id=\"ph1\">`^[0-9A-Z][-.\\w]*(?&lt;=[0-9A-Z])\\$$`</ph>.","pos":[26776,26879],"source":" For example, the part number regular expression can be rewritten as `^[0-9A-Z][-.\\w]*(?<=[0-9A-Z])\\$$`."},{"content":"This regular expression pattern is defined as shown in the following table.","pos":[26880,26955]},{"content":"Pattern","pos":[26962,26969]},{"content":"Description","pos":[26970,26981]},{"content":"Begin the match at the beginning of the input string.","pos":[27026,27079]},{"content":"Match an alphanumeric character.","pos":[27095,27127]},{"content":"The part number must consist of at least this character.","pos":[27128,27184]},{"content":"Match zero or more occurrences of any word character, hyphen, or period.","pos":[27199,27271]},{"content":"Match a dollar sign.","pos":[27281,27301]},{"content":"Look ahead of the ending dollar sign to ensure that the previous character is alphanumeric.","pos":[27322,27413]},{"content":"End the match at the end of the input string.","pos":[27422,27467]},{"content":"The following example illustrates the use of this regular expression to match an array containing possible part numbers.","pos":[27475,27595]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[!code-csharp</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#11<ept id=\"p2\">](../../../samples/snippets/csharp/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/cs/backtrack4.cs#11)</ept><ept id=\"p1\">]</ept>","pos":[27602,27778],"source":"[!code-csharp[Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#11](../../../samples/snippets/csharp/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/cs/backtrack4.cs#11)]"},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[!code-vb</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#11<ept id=\"p2\">](../../../samples/snippets/visualbasic/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/vb/backtrack4.vb#11)</ept><ept id=\"p1\">]</ept>","pos":[27780,27957],"source":"[!code-vb[Conceptual.RegularExpressions.BestPractices#11](../../../samples/snippets/visualbasic/VS_Snippets_CLR/conceptual.regularexpressions.bestpractices/vb/backtrack4.vb#11)]"},{"content":"The regular expression language in .NET includes the following language elements that you can use to eliminate nested quantifiers.","pos":[27964,28094]},{"content":"For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Grouping Constructs<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../docs/standard/base-types/grouping-constructs-in-regular-expressions.md)</ept>.","pos":[28095,28224],"source":" For more information, see [Grouping Constructs](../../../docs/standard/base-types/grouping-constructs-in-regular-expressions.md)."},{"content":"Language element","pos":[28231,28247]},{"content":"Description","pos":[28248,28259]},{"pos":[28309,28334],"content":"<ph id=\"ph1\">`(?=`</ph> <ph id=\"ph2\">`subexpression`</ph> <ph id=\"ph3\">`)`</ph>","source":"`(?=` `subexpression` `)`"},{"content":"Zero-width positive lookahead.","pos":[28335,28365]},{"content":"Look ahead of the current position to determine whether <ph id=\"ph1\">`subexpression`</ph> matches the input string.","pos":[28366,28463],"source":" Look ahead of the current position to determine whether `subexpression` matches the input string."},{"pos":[28468,28493],"content":"<ph id=\"ph1\">`(?!`</ph> <ph id=\"ph2\">`subexpression`</ph> <ph id=\"ph3\">`)`</ph>","source":"`(?!` `subexpression` `)`"},{"content":"Zero-width negative lookahead.","pos":[28494,28524]},{"content":"Look ahead of the current position to determine whether <ph id=\"ph1\">`subexpression`</ph> does not match the input string.","pos":[28525,28629],"source":" Look ahead of the current position to determine whether `subexpression` does not match the input string."},{"pos":[28634,28660],"content":"<ph id=\"ph1\">`(?&lt;=`</ph> <ph id=\"ph2\">`subexpression`</ph> <ph id=\"ph3\">`)`</ph>","source":"`(?<=` `subexpression` `)`"},{"content":"Zero-width positive lookbehind.","pos":[28661,28692]},{"content":"Look behind the current position to determine whether <ph id=\"ph1\">`subexpression`</ph> matches the input string.","pos":[28693,28788],"source":" Look behind the current position to determine whether `subexpression` matches the input string."},{"pos":[28793,28819],"content":"<ph id=\"ph1\">`(?&lt;!`</ph> <ph id=\"ph2\">`subexpression`</ph> <ph id=\"ph3\">`)`</ph>","source":"`(?<!` `subexpression` `)`"},{"content":"Zero-width negative lookbehind.","pos":[28820,28851]},{"content":"Look behind the current position to determine whether <ph id=\"ph1\">`subexpression`</ph> does not match the input string.","pos":[28852,28954],"source":" Look behind the current position to determine whether `subexpression` does not match the input string."},{"pos":[28962,28981],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Back to top<ept id=\"p1\">](#top)</ept>","source":"[Back to top](#top)"},{"pos":[29017,29036],"content":"Use Time-out Values","linkify":"Use Time-out Values","nodes":[{"content":"Use Time-out Values","pos":[0,19]}]},{"content":"If your regular expressions processes input that nearly matches the regular expression pattern, it can often rely on excessive backtracking, which impacts its performance significantly.","pos":[29040,29225]},{"content":"In addition to carefully considering your use of backtracking and testing the regular expression against near-matching input, you should always set a time-out value to ensure that the impact of excessive backtracking, if it occurs, is minimized.","pos":[29226,29471]},{"content":"The regular expression time-out interval defines the period of time that the regular expression engine will look for a single match before it times out. The default time-out interval is <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.RegularExpressions.Regex.InfiniteMatchTimeout?displayProperty=fullName&gt;</ph>, which means that the regular expression will not time out. You can override this value and define a time-out interval as follows:","pos":[29478,29884],"source":"The regular expression time-out interval defines the period of time that the regular expression engine will look for a single match before it times out. The default time-out interval is <xref:System.Text.RegularExpressions.Regex.InfiniteMatchTimeout?displayProperty=fullName>, which means that the regular expression will not time out. You can override this value and define a time-out interval as follows:"},{"content":"By providing a time-out value when you instantiate a <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Text.RegularExpressions.Regex&gt;</ph> object by calling the <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Text.RegularExpressions.Regex.%23ctor%28System.String%2CSystem.Text.RegularExpressions.RegexOptions%2CSystem.TimeSpan%29?displayProperty=fullName&gt;</ph> constructor.","pos":[29894,30185],"source":"By providing a time-out value when you instantiate a <xref:System.Text.RegularExpressions.Regex> object by calling the <xref:System.Text.RegularExpressions.Regex.%23ctor%28System.String%2CSystem.Text.RegularExpressions.RegexOptions%2CSystem.TimeSpan%29?displayProperty=fullName> constructor."},{"pos":[3